1844	\begin{proof}
1845	  \uses{def:gr_glued_scheme, lem:gr_separated, def:gr_transition}
1846	  Since \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is of finite type
1847	  (\cref{def:gr_glued_scheme}) and separated (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), and
1848	  \(\mathbb{Z}\) is Noetherian, properness follows from the valuative criterion
1849	  for discrete valuation rings: it suffices to show that every solid diagram
1850	  \[
1851	    \begin{array}{ccc}
1852	      \Spec K & \xrightarrow{\ \varphi\ } & \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \\
1853	      \downarrow & & \downarrow \pi \\
1854	      \Spec R & \longrightarrow & \Spec \mathbb{Z}
1855	    \end{array}
1856	  \]
1857	  with \(R\) a discrete valuation ring, \(K = \operatorname{Frac}(R)\) and
1858	  valuation \(\nu : K \to \mathbb{Z} \cup \{\infty\}\), admits a unique diagonal
1859	  filler \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\).
1860	
1861	  \emph{Existence.} The morphism \(\varphi : \Spec K \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) lands
1862	  in some chart \(U^I\) (\(\Spec K\) has one point), so it is given by a ring map
1863	  \(f : \mathbb{Z}[X^I] \to K\). Among the \(\binom{r}{d}\) minors choose \(J\)
1864	  with \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\) minimal. Because \(P^I_I = 1\) gives \(f(P^I_I) = 1\)
1865	  with \(\nu = 0\), the minimum satisfies \(\nu(f(P^I_J)) \le 0\); in particular
1866	  \(f(P^I_J) \ne 0\), so \(f(X^I_J) \in \mathrm{GL}_d(K)\) is invertible over
1867	  \(K\). Define
1868	  \[
1869	    g : \mathbb{Z}[X^J] \longrightarrow K, \qquad
1870	    g(X^J) = f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\bigr) ;
1871	  \]
1872	  this is the composite of \(\theta_{I,J}\) (\cref{def:gr_transition}) with
1873	  \(f\), so \(g\) defines the same \(K\)-point \(\varphi\), now exhibited as
1874	  landing in \(U^J\).
1875	
1876	  We show every entry \(g(x^J_{p,q})\) lies in \(R\), i.e.\ has \(\nu \ge 0\).
1877	  First, for any size-\(d\) subset \(K' \subseteq \{1,\dots,r\}\) the \(K'\)-minor
1878	  of \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\) is \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\), so
1879	  \[
1880	    g(P^J_{K'}) = \det f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\bigr)
1881	    = \frac{f(P^I_{K'})}{f(P^I_J)},
1882	    \qquad
1883	    \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) = \nu(f(P^I_{K'})) - \nu(f(P^I_J)) \ge 0
1884	  \]
1885	  by minimality of \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\). Now the \(J\)-minor \(X^J_J\) of \(X^J\) is
1886	  the identity, so by cofactor expansion each individual entry
1887	  \(x^J_{p,q}\) (with \(q \notin J\)) equals, up to sign, the minor
1888	  \(P^J_{K'}\) for \(K' = (J \setminus \{j_p\}) \cup \{q\}\) -- the \(d \times d\)
1889	  determinant obtained by replacing the \(p\)-th identity column of \(X^J_J\) by
1890	  the column \(q\). Hence \(\nu(g(x^J_{p,q})) = \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) \ge 0\) for all
1891	  entries, and the entries with \(q \in J\) are \(0\) or \(1\). Therefore
1892	  \(g(\mathbb{Z}[X^J]) \subseteq R\), so \(g\) factors uniquely as
1893	  \(\mathbb{Z}[X^J] \to R \hookrightarrow K\). The corresponding morphism
1894	  \(\Spec R \to U^J \hookrightarrow \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) restricts to \(\varphi\)
1895	  over \(\Spec K\) and lies over \(\Spec \mathbb{Z}\), providing the filler.
1896	
1897	  \emph{Uniqueness.} Any two fillers agree over the generic point \(\Spec K\)
1898	  and, \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) being separated over \(\mathbb{Z}\)
1899	  (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), two morphisms \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\)
1900	  agreeing on the schematically dense open \(\Spec K\) coincide. This verifies
1901	  the valuative criterion, so \(\pi : \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is
1902	  proper.
1903	\end{proof}
